column16: ,"content":{"body":"\u003Cp\u003EPart-time or casual work is something that almost all students will undertake at some point in their university career. Not only does it help pay the bills
column17: , and start savings for the future
column18: , but it provides students with valuable experience that will look good on their resumes
column19:
, and teaches skills that will be valuable for future life and work with employers.

What kinds of part-time jobs are there?

There are many different kinds of part-time jobs available to university students. The most common categories are listed below: 

  • Administration and Data-Entry
  • Call Centre
  • Hospitality and Catering
  • Marketing and Sales
  • Retail

Within each of these categories are a variety of overlapping jobs that may be available to students. For example
column20: , in the retail category a worker may be both a salesperson and a customer service representative. This will depend on the size of the organisation – smaller businesses demand more flexibility from their workers – for example a corner coffee shop may require the barista to help as one of the wait-staff during busy periods
column21: , whereas a larger chain store is more likely to have specialised workers for each role.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Ch4\u003EWhat kinds of organisations offer part-time jobs?\u003C\u002Fh4\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThere is a constant demand for part-time or casual workers in the Australian economy
column22: , both from small businesses and large organisations. This is especially true in the hospitality and retail industries – corporate giants like Woolworths
column24: , Starbucks and Bunnings as well as local boutique stores
column25: , family grocers and cafes all require part-time staff. Administration and data entry has the largest potential market – including non-profit
column26: , services and the public sector as well as private enterprise. For the call centre and marketing categories the employers tend to be large companies
column27: , like Telstra.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Ch4\u003EWhat skills do I need to get a part-time job?\u003C\u002Fh4\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe kinds of jobs advertised as part-time usually do not require specialised professional skills
column28: , certain specialised jobs may require marketing
column30: , IT or other experience. More general skills
column31:
, applicable across multiple sectors include:

  • Interpersonal and communication skills
  • Diligence
  • Teamwork
  • Leadership
  • Time management
  • The ability to perform under pressure
  • The ability to get on well with others

How much will I be paid?

Payment for part-time work will vary depending on the industry
column32: , size of organisation and responsibilities involved. The minimum wage is $16.87 per hour. Casual work will offer higher rates
column33: , usually starting from around $18-22 per hour.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Ch4\u003EHow can I find part-time work?\u003C\u002Fh4\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EDespite the prevalence of part-time work in the economy
column34: , it can seem difficult to find job opportunities. One of the main reasons for this is that a lot of part-time or casual work is required by organisations (such as small businesses) on an \u003Cem\u003Ead-hoc\u003C\u002Fem\u003E basis
column35: , meaning they don’t advertise on the web or in print publications like the “classified” section of the local paper. Instead
column36: , the organisation may put up a “staff wanted” sign in their window
column37: , or not advertise at all. The solution in this case is to approach a variety of small businesses in your neighbourhood (such as shops or coffee shops) and express your interest in a part-time job. At this point they may not need your services
column38: , but will usually be impressed with your initiative. If you submit your resume to them
column39: , they will keep you in mind next time a staff position opens up. Approaching small businesses directly this way makes their job much easier
column40: , as often they have little time or money to spend on recruitment efforts
column41: , and so will be more likely to look at your application with favour. The direct approach is the best way to find part-time jobs in the SME sector
column42: , but it is also worth trying for larger organisations that don’t advertise part-time work.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003ELarger organisations may have a structured employment application process. Examples include food retailers like KFC
column43: , Domino’s Pizza and Baker’s Delight – all of which have online application processes. An aspiring student submits their resume for a position in one of the local franchises. Sometimes you will be able to do this even if no positions are currently available (in which case the organisation will keep the application on hold for the next available job). Other times you will have to keep checking back to see when the applications open.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe last method of part-time job searching is checking job websites and print classifieds for part-time positions. While some fantastic jobs (potentially higher-paid ones) may be found this way
column44: , these opportunities represent only a proportion of the massive job market out there. This is because unlike graduate or full-time work
column45: , most part-time employers don’t pay much to advertise their part-time jobs (especially if they can get the job filled without advertising). In addition
column46: , some of the “jobs” found online are scams too
column47: , offering “experience” for work that really should be paid. Because many students believe that scouring online for work opportunities is the best way to find a part-time job
column48: , those jobs that \u003Cem\u003Eare\u003C\u002Fem\u003E advertised will also have many more people competing with them than the average unadvertised local job. In conclusion
column49: , searching print and online is but one method that a determined job-seeker should employ.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\r\n\u003Ch4\u003EInternational students and part-time work in Australia\u003C\u002Fh4\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EFinding a job while on a student visa can be a challenge
column50: , as there are more limited opportunities (and work hours) available to international students. During term time
column51: , international students may not work more than 40 hours per fortnight
column52: , however during holiday period there are no restrictions on hours worked. It is recommended that international students target small businesses for jobs
column53: , as they do not require permanent residency visas or citizenship (as some larger businesses do
